@sdedic sorry, a complicated sounding way of describing something quite simple :smile:  I mean that putting further logic in to resolve a path to an image hard-coded in this class is wrong IMO.  The dark LAF stuff is horrible!  A better approach would be to allow people to register a provider to override the resolution of -

```
public static final Image loadImage(String resource, boolean localized)
```
That way we can not only support what you're trying to do here, but people can develop modules for high-res icons, icon fonts, svg, icon themes, etc. too.

And yes, probably better on the mailing list!

@rtaneja1 , There was on overlapping jars warning in verification. I have added the changes to `ignored-overlaps` file. I tried running the tests, but the tests are failing due to the same reason with/without my changes.

I could not see any place where `struts-config_1_2-custom.dtd` or `struts-config_1_3-custom.dtd` are being used in the codebase, so I think it would be okay if we don't include them.

I see that there is a merge conflict. I will resolve it and squash the commits once this PR is approved.

@matthiasblaesing , I see that instead of collecting the `*.dtd` files from different jars, you added them directly along with licenseinfo.xml. The rest of your changes also make sense. 

Without `struts-config_1_3-custom.dtd`, was the build failing at the root folder? Because, I tried building just the `web.struts` module without `struts-config_1_3-custom.dtd` file and the build was passed for the module.

So, we have two options to go forward from here, I can close this PR and you can merge your commits, as they contain all the necessary changes exhaustively, or I can cherry pick your commits, squash them, and then merge the changes through this PR. Which way do you think we should go forward with?

I wanted to open a ticket with apache legal with that question. I found this:

https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/LEGAL-408

@ehsavoie already opened the issue and my reading of the answer is: We can't include/distribute the schema (that was IMHO clear already) and we also can't distribute generated code. (@ehsavoie if you understand it differently please chime in)

@arusinha this also affects `j2ee.weblogic9` there the situation is even worse: As we have no license for the weblogic XSDs, there is no basis for generating code and/or including the weblogic XSDs

At this point I'm tempted to suggest to remove both modules.

@geertjanw The XSDs/DTDs are used to generate code and my interpretation of the reply from apache legal is, that the license transcends to the generated code. So for weblogic we would distribute unlicensed code (i.e. we have no right to distribute) and for jboss/wildfly we would distribute LGPL code, which is against the ASF rules.
Getting the XSDs/DTDs at runtime would be perfectly doable, but the modules would need to be reworked to no rely on code generated at build-time.

@vikasprabhakar the DTD files are present here:
https://www.jboss.org/j2ee/dtd/
The files are missing an explicit license and as such I would assume they are covered by the projects LGPL license. That at least is reflected in some of the XSDs I saw. Asking redhat would most probably reveal the same. That still leaves us with the "wrong" license.

@emilianbold Would you mind having a quick look to OK the API change here, which is just the addition of a new utility class "VectorIcon"?

I looked at the retina-related work you did in the past. This PR should should not interfere with any of that, as this PR only touches the LAF-related icons, and does not change ImageUtilities in any way. It would be great to eventually merge your work as well.

(There are basically two possible approaches to doing HiDPI icons: either via MultiResolutionImage, or via vector-painted custom implementations of the Icon class. I think both approaches should be supported--this PR deals with the vector painting approach, while your previous retina work deals with the MultiResolutionImage approach. The MultiResolutionImage approach currently does not work properly on Windows, due to https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8212226 , but surely it will work in the long-term.)
